SIMPLE: lovely
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Lovely
<hw>Love"ly</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos>
<adjf>Lovelier</adjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos>
<adjf>Loveliest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[AS. <ets>luflic</ets>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>Having such an appearance as excites, or is fitted to
excite, love; beautiful; charming; very pleasing in form, looks, tone,
or manner.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Lovely</xex> to look on.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Piers
Plowman.</au>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Not one so fair of face, of speech so <qex>lovely</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Robert of Brunne.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If I had such a tire, this face of mine⟦br⟧
Were full as <qex>lovely</qex> as is this of hers.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Lovable; amiable; having qualities of any kind which
excite, or are fitted to excite, love or friendship.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A most <qex>lovely</qex> gentlemanlike man.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Loving; tender.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧A
<xex>lovely</xex> kiss.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Many a <qex>lovely</qex> look on them he cast.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Very pleasing; -- applied loosely to almost anything
which is not grand or merely pretty; <as>as, a <ex>lovely</ex> view; a
<ex>lovely</ex> valley; a <ex>lovely</ex> melody.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Indeed these fields⟦br⟧
Are <qex>lovely</qex>, <qex>lovelier</qex> not the Elysian lawns.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Beautiful; charming; delightful; delectable;
enchanting; lovable; amiable.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lovely</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Lovely
<hw>Love"ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a manner to please, or to
excite love.</def> <mark>[Obs. or R.]</mark>
<rj><au>Tyndale.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Love-making</ent>⟦br⟧
